First model: Pctcover as a predictor.

\[ \begin{align*} y &\sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda) \\ \log(\lambda) &= a \text{Pctcover} + b \end{align*} \]

scatter(dat.PCTCOVER, dat.SALAMAN)
function salamander_loglik1(p, counts, pctcover) 
    a, b = p
    λ = exp.(a * pctcover .+ b)
    ll = sum(logpdf.(Poisson.(λ), counts))
    return ll
end

function sim_salamanders1(p, pctcover, n)
    a, b = p
    λ = exp.(a * pctcover .+ b)
    sal_pred = zeros(n, length(pctcover))
    for i = 1:length(pctcover)
        sal_pred[:, i] = rand(Poisson(λ[i]), n)
    end
    return sal_pred
end

function salamander_loglik2(p, counts, pctcover, forestage) 
    a1, a2, b = p
    λ = exp.(a1 * pctcover + a2 * forestage .+ b)
    ll = sum(logpdf.(Poisson.(λ), counts))
    return ll
end

function hurricane_loglik2(p, counts, fem) 
    a, b = p
    λ = exp.(a * fem .+ b)
    ll = sum(logpdf.(Poisson.(λ), counts))
    return ll
end

function hurricane_intonly(p, counts) 
    b = p
    λ = exp.(b)
    ll = sum(logpdf.(Poisson.(λ), counts))
    return ll
end

function sim_hurricanes(p, femininity, n)
    a, b = p
    λ = exp.(a * femininity .+ b)
    hur_pred = zeros(n, length(femininity))
    for i = 1:length(femininity)
        hur_pred[:, i] = rand(Poisson(λ[i]), n)
    end
    return hur_pred
end
